<section xml:id="end-behavior-polynomial-functions">
    <title>End Behavior of Polynomial Functions</title>
    <p>When graphing a polynomial or any other type of function, we focus on illustrating its key features and allow the curve to exit the visible region once its overall direction is clear. 
        The pattern that describes how the values of <m>p(x)</m> increase or decrease as <m>x</m> approaches <m>\pm\infty</m> is known as the <term>end behavior</term> of the function. 
        In particular, polynomials have four different types of end behavior.
        The Leading Coefficient Test gives an efficient way to quickly tell which of the four different end behaviors a polynomial has.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="leading-coefficient-test">
  <title>The Leading Coefficient Test</title>
  <statement>
    <p>Let <m>p</m> be any polynomial function with leading term <m>a_n x^n</m>. The following figures describe the four different types of end behavior a polynomial function may have.</p>
  

  <figure>
    <caption>For odd degree polynomials, the graph will have opposite end behaviors.</caption>
    <sidebyside>

      <figure>
        <caption><p>If <m>a_n &gt; 0</m> and <m>n</m> is odd, then
  <ul>
    <li><p><m>p(x)</m> will approach <m>+\infty</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>+\infty</m>,</p></li>
    <li><p><m>p(x)</m> will approach <m>-\infty</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>-\infty</m>, and</p></li>
    <li><p>we draw an arrow rising up to the right and an arrow falling down to the left.</p></li>
  </ul>
</p>
</caption>
        <image source="chapter-5/odd_positive_end_behavior.png">
          <shortdescription>The graph of an odd degree polynomial with positive leading coefficient.</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure>
        <caption><p>If <m>a_n &lt; 0</m> and <m>n</m> is odd, then
  <ul>
    <li><p> <m>p(x)</m> will approach <m>-\infty</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>+\infty</m>,</p></li>
        <li><p><m>p(x)</m> will approach <m>+\infty</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>-\infty</m>, and</p></li>
    <li><p>we draw an arrow falling down to the right and an arrow rising up to the left.</p></li>
  </ul>
</p>
</caption>
        <image source="chapter-5/odd_negative_end_behavior.png">
          <shortdescription>The graph of an odd degree polynomial with negative leading coefficient.</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>
  </figure>

  <figure>
    <caption>For even degree polynomials, the graph will have the same end behaviors.</caption>
    <sidebyside>

      <figure>
        <caption><p>If <m>a_n &gt; 0</m> and <m>n</m> is even, then
  <ul>
    <li><p><m>p(x)</m> will approach <m>+\infty</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>+\infty</m>,</p></li>
    <li><p><m>p(x)</m> will approach <m>+\infty</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>-\infty</m>, and</p></li>
    <li><p>we draw an arrow rising up to the right and an arrow rising up to the left.</p></li>
  </ul>
</p>
</caption>
        <image source="chapter-5/even_positive_end_behavior.png">
          <shortdescription>The graph of an even degree polynomial with positive leading coefficient.</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure>
        <caption><p>If <m>a_n &lt; 0</m>  and <m>n</m> is even, then
  <ul>
    <li><p><m>p(x)</m> will approach <m>-\infty</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>+\infty</m>,</p></li>
    <li><p><m>p(x)</m> will approach <m>-\infty</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>-\infty</m>, and</p></li>
    <li><p>we draw an arrow falling down to the right and an arrow falling down to the left.</p></li>
  </ul>
</p>
</caption>
        <image source="chapter-5/even_negative_end_behavior.png">
          <shortdescription>The graph of an even degree polynomial with negative leading coefficient.</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </sidebyside>
  </figure>
  </statement>
</theorem>
<example xml:id="using-leading-coefficient-test-v1">
  <title>Using the Leading Coefficient Test, version 1</title>

  <statement>
    <p>Determine the end behavior of <m>p(x) = x^5 - x + 3</m>.</p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>Since this is an odd degree polynomial with a positive leading coefficient, the graph will rise to the right and fall to the left.</p>

    <figure>
      <caption>The graph of <m>p(x) = x^5 - x + 3</m>.</caption>
      <image source="chapter-5/example_odd_positive_end_behavior.png" decorative="yes" width="50%"/>
    </figure>
  </solution>
</example>
<example xml:id="using-leading-coefficient-test-v1b">
  <title>Using the Leading Coefficient Test, version 2</title>

  <statement>
    <p>Determine the end behavior of <m>p(x) = -x^3 + x^2 + 1</m>.</p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>Since this is an odd degree polynomial with a negative leading coefficient, the graph will fall to the right and rise to the left.</p>

    <figure>
      <caption>The graph of <m>p(x) = -x^3 + x^2 + 1</m>.</caption>
      <image source="chapter-5/example_odd_negative_end_behavior.png" decorative="yes" width="50%" />
    </figure>
  </solution>
</example>
<example xml:id="using-leading-coefficient-test-v3">
  <title>Using the Leading Coefficient Test, version 3</title>

  <statement>
    <p>Determine the end behavior of <m>p(x) = 3x^4 + 3x^3 - 15x^2 + 3x - 18</m>.</p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>Since this is an even degree polynomial with a positive leading coefficient, the graph will rise to the right and rise to the left.</p>

    <figure>
      <caption>The graph of <m>p(x) = 3x^4 + 3x^3 - 15x^2 + 3x - 18</m>.</caption>
      <image source="chapter-5/example_even_positive_end_behavior.png" decorative="yes" width="50%" />
    </figure>
  </solution>
</example>
<example xml:id="using-leading-coefficient-test-v4">
  <title>Using the Leading Coefficient Test, version 4</title>

  <statement>
    <p>Determine the end behavior of <m>p(x) = -2x^4-4x^3+26x^2+28x-48</m>.</p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>Since this is an even degree polynomial with a negative leading coefficient, the graph will fall to the right and fall to the left.</p>

    <figure>
      <caption>The graph of <m>p(x)=-2x^4-4x^3+26x^2+28x-48</m>.</caption>
      <image source="chapter-5/example_even_negative_end_behavior.png" decorative="yes" width="50%" />
    </figure>
  </solution>
</example>
</section>